Here's the standard approach:

**1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`**

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
    <!-- ... more tokens ... -->
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**2. Create a theme service to swap dictionaries at runtime**

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Themes.LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** The `IThemeDictionary` marker interface (just `interface IThemeDictionary {}`) on each theme XAML code-behind makes the "find and remove" step reliable. Alternatively, you can track the current dictionary in a field.

**3. Load the saved theme on startup in `App.xaml.cs`**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
    }
}
```

**4. Reference theme tokens with `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`)**

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" />
</ContentPage>
```

`DynamicResource` is the key — it re-evaluates when the underlying dictionary changes, giving you the instant swap.

**5. Wire up your settings page**

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>High Contrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var theme = ThemePicker.SelectedIndex switch
    {
        1 => AppTheme.Dark,
        2 => AppTheme.HighContrast,
        _ => AppTheme.Light,
    };
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`DynamicResource` everywhere** — `StaticResource` won't update when the dictionary swaps.
- **`Preferences`** persists the user's choice across app restarts.
- Keep every theme dictionary's keys identical so you never hit a missing-key fallback.
